Foley Van Dam Feiner Hughes Computer Graphics book is certainly a good Chapter is Viewing in then read chapter Visible Surface Determination For more information go to chapter for shading chapter for clipping and branch out from Quantizing bit images down to Find a copy of Color Image Quantization for Frame Buffer Display by Paul Heckbert SIGGRAPH ' Proceedings page There are other algorithms but this one works well and is fairly Implementations are included in most raster toolkits see item below A variant method is described in Graphics Gems Note that the code from the Graphics Gems series is all available from an FTP site as described Check out John Bradley's Diversity Algorithm which is incorporated into the xv package and described in the back of the The ImageMagick package see section for where it is contains another quantizing algorithm which is presented as doing a better job than the other algorithms but slower There's also an implementation of Wan Wong and Prusinkiewicz An Algorithm for Multidimensional Data Clustering Transactions on Mathematical Software June avialable as pub Graphics This code in modified form appears in the Utah Raster Toolkit as Converting color into The NTSC formula is luminosity red green blue Quantizing grayscale to black The only reference you need for this stuff is Digital Halftoning Robert Ulichney MIT Press ISBN But before you go off and start coding check out the image manipulation software mentioned in item All of the packages mentioned can do some form of gray to b w Rotating a raster image by an arbitrary The obvious but wrong method is to loop over the pixels in the source image transform each coordinate and copy the pixel to the This is wrong because it leaves holes in the Instead loop over the pixels in the destination image apply the reverse transformation to the coordinates and copy that pixel from the This method is quite general and can be used for any one to one D mapping not just You can add anti aliasing by doing sub pixel However there is a much faster method with antialising included which involves doing three shear The method was originally created for the IM Raster Toolkit see below an implementation is also present in Reference A Fast Algorithm for Raster Rotation by Alan Paeth Graphics Interface ' Vancouver An article on the IM toolkit appears in the same An updated version of the rotation paper appears in Graphics Gems see section under the original Free image manipulation There are a number of toolkits for converting from one image format to another doing simple image manipulations such as size scaling plus the above mentioned color gray gray b w Here are pointers to some of them xv by John X based image display manipulation and format conversion XV displays many image formats and permits editing of GIF files among The program was updated see the file contrib xv on PBMPLUS by Jef Comprehensive format conversion and image manipulation The latest version is always available via anonymous FTP as pbmplus graphics graphics packages pbmplus pbmplus and contrib pbmplus IM Raster Toolkit by Alan Paeth Provides a portable and efficient format and related The format is versatile in supporting pixels of arbitrary channels components and bit precisions while allowing compression and machine byte order The kit contains more than tools with extensive support of image manipulation digital halftoning and format Previously distributed on tape c o the University of Waterloo an FTP version will appear Utah RLE Conversion and manipulation package similar to Available via FTP as pub urt pub Graphics urt and pub urt Fuzzy Pixmap Manipulation by Michael Mauldin Conversion and manipulation package similar to Version available via FTP as usr mlm ftp pub and graphics Img Software Set by Paul Raveling Reads and writes its own image format displays on an screen and does some image Version is available via FTP as contrib img and pub img along with a large collection of color Xim X Image Manipulat